'''Cert-money''', or '''head-money''', was a common [[Fine (penalty)|fine]], paid annually by the residents of several [[manorialism|manor]]s to the lords thereof; and sometimes to the [[Hundred (division)|hundred]]; ''pro certo letae'', for the certain keeping of the [[Court leet|leet]]. This in ancient records, was called ''certum letae''.<ref>{{cite book | editor-last = Chambers| editor-first = Ephraim| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Cyclopaedia, Or an Universal Dictionary of Arts and Sciences| publisher = | series = | volume = | edition = | date = 1728| location = | pages = | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Cbc9VS_1QKEC&pg=PT355| doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>

